If you want to try the test sometime, this is what the results mean: A high score in Stimulation suggests that you are a smoker who is stimulated by the cigarette — you feel that it helps wake you, organize your thoughts, and keep you going.A high score in Handling suggests that you feel satisfied by handling cigarettes.A high score in Pleasure Relaxation suggests that using cigarettes makes you feel good.A high score in Crutch: Tension Reduction suggests you use cigarettes as a crutch in moments of stress or discomfort.A high score in Craving: Psychological Addiction suggests you are psychologically addicted to cigarettes. 15. Gradually reducing the amount you smoke can also lead to quitting. Do you think gradual reduction could be right for you? #beingconscious
I've been slowing my smoking down already so hopefully it will work for me. I plan on quitting soon.
What would you miss most if you quit smoking for good? #TDII

13.Asking you to go out and party, even though they know drinking is a trigger, would NOT be helpful. Joking about how long you’ll stay on the quit wagon would NOT be helpful. What other things could you ask your friends NOT to do to keep you on the right path? #support
Avoid smoking near me. Don't harass me about quitting. Don't offer me.any cigs. Things like that

data.message: 10.What are your top reasons for quitting? #freeyourself
I have a child on the way that needs me around for a while and I can't afford cigarettes and diapers. Also for health reasons
9. Write a list of all the reasons why you want to quit, and post it somewhere prominent where you will frequently see it. Which spot did you choose, and why will it work for you? #reinforcement
I picked on my bedroom door because ill see it everyday and it will keep my motivation for quitting in my head.
8. Check out this site to see just how much $ you've given to Big Tobacco. Share your numbers here and vow to stop throwing away your hard-earned cash! #beingconscioushttp://buff.ly/1695CyZ
35064 cigarettes or 1753 packs. That's a carp load of money haha.
Holy smokes! 7300 stoges, 365 packs.

7. Flavored cigarettes have been outlawed for years now, yet e-cig companies are using old tricks to gain new customers while they still can. Would you have started smoking at an earlier age if the product you used was flavored like your favorite candy? #ecig
It definitely would make it more appealing but I already started atpretty young age.

Probably, if something was candy flavored, I'd try anything. I don't think they are directly marketing to kids, rather than just competing with the next guy. It wouldn't stop them from selling candy flavors just because its more appealing to young people though.
Hi everyone and welcome to TSP! I am available for the next hour. Let me know if you have any questions! #TDII
I'd like to know how addictive cigarettes are. I've heard they're more addicting than heroin.

Hi 10093, good question - a direct comparison is pretty hard to make since only a very few people will try heroin in the first place. But yes you are right, cigarettes are all the way up there in terms of their addictiveness.
Thanks so much. I think it'd be cool if you or someone else at the study could make a post explaining the benefits of quitting both short and long term.

Sure - I have plenty of material around that. Aside from the monetary and social consequences and the improvement for quality of life there are also a lot of short and long term health consequences. I will talk more about this throughout the program but for now check out this picture. Does this motivate you to quit?
Being able to smell and breathe is motivation enough haha.
Sound good 10093! Have you given any thought to deciding on a quit day yet?
Not an exact date no. I have PRobably three or four packs left so it will be sopn
Cool! How much do you currently smoke and how confident are you that you will be successful?
Around a half a pack a day. And I'm pretty confident. If I set my mind to something I accomplish it.
Sounds great 10093! So just quickly doing the math - at this rate you should be done with your current supply about one week from now. Do you have a strategy how to deal with cravings once you quit?
I've got to run. See you next week!
Thanks again.

6. For any of you who aren’t sure what an e-cig is, take a look at this FDA page explaining what they are and some of the controversy surrounding their regulation. If you were a minor, do you think an e-cig would be more appealing and “safer” to try than a traditional cigarette? #beingconscioushttp://buff.ly/1zPTMXq
I think the fact that more people smoke real cigarettes makes them more "appealing" but I do believe that e-cigs are marketed as a "safer" alternative to smoking.
I sure thought they were more appealing, i started with those and then went on to real cigarettes, not saying that they make people want to start but they definitely make it easier to try a real cig,

I never smoked on campus but I could get away with vaping in class. So yeah, I found that more appealing and thought it was a lotsafer.I ended up vaping more because it was extremely accessible. It could possibly be more habit forming.

2. What is keeping quitting smoking from the top of your priorities list? What would make quitting even more important to you? If you put down 10 for yesterday's post, why is quitting so important to you and how did it get to the top of your priorities list? #motivation
Quitting is important for my health. It got to the top when i realized how it effected me
I agree. For better health reasons, I cant afford it anymore and I have a child on the way.
it's important to me because I have a child on the way, I don't want her to be effected by my choices & financially it adds up.

Smoking long term isn't worth it. Learning to quit would be helpful in how to deal with addiction & temptation. It is literally one of the most irrational acts for one's health. It's like living a paradox, knowing its like a lottery for all sorts of health problems, but being aware of the facts sometimes just doesn't seem important.
10114, great point- Victoria from TSP
3. Have any of you used a quit program or counseling program before? There are lots of free programs out there- how could they benefit you? What would make them better? #beingconscious
No, I haven't tried any quitting programs.
I haven't tried any either.
Never considered it but I'd like to, any kind of help is always welcomeIt takes a true mature person to know when you need to accept help regardless of where it come from
Good point, 10072 !- Victoria from TSP
No, I would read tips & tricks, but no hotlines or support groups.
4. Take this test to see how addicted to nicotine you are. What’s your reaction to your score? Are you surprised? #beingconscious http://buff.ly/15M6ES6
My score was three or moderately dependent. I'm not surprised. I'm aware that I'm addicted to.cigarettes and it's a habit I need.to.change.
My score was a 2, like 10093 said I'm not very suprised, i can see that I'm addicted to cigarettes and i can see when my attention is pulled away by just seeing or smelling one
My score was 1. I am addicted somewhat to cigarettes, but it's mostly a bad habit that i know i can easily get rid of.
I scored a 3. The smoking with illness is the most sickening cig for me.

5. Big tobacco companies aim to make their brand as appealing as possible --become more conscious and learn to critique cigarette ads. In the ads below, how is Camel trying to manipulate its customers? #beingconscious
I think they're trying.to make it seem cool, enjoyable and attractive.

Being aware of the "cool factor" doesn't make me want to smoke. I think it effects impressionable teens more than adults, though. Smoking in movies is the best way to get to me, I hate when they smoke my brand scene after scene...

I've been looking for a job and working out, i can feel my need for cigarettes going down I'm really struggling with the after meal cigarette though, i feel like once its the onky cigarette I've had in the day it should stop being an issue, I've managed to cut down from 4 to 5 cigarettes a day to at least 2 a day though, I've noticed slight to moderate exercise when craving a cigarette works to get the need out of my mind

Had a few cigarettes today, probably shouldn't have bought a new pack but its gonna be hard with all the things going on in my life right now, they say when you go to AA to not try and quit smoking and drinking at the same time because you'll fail on both if you have one of either, i think I'm just gonna have to wein my self off of them slowly as my life gets back on track
Hey group took my first survey today. Wondering if I can really stop smoking. But in the mean time 💨💨💨

It helps to have someone to talk to about quiting actually going through the same situation, especially living in a smoking home it sure is nice to have support, while i may add that i have had a cigarette today /:

data.message: Is there such thing as a least harmful cigarette brand? Or do all brand cause the same damage to the body? I know Marlboros are pretty strong, so are Newports and camels but I've gotten into the so called "natural" king mountain cigarettes
I've heard American spirits are better for you.
I doubt it but that's the rumor haha

Hi 10072, I don't know of any "less harmful" cigarettes. The tobacco industry tried to sell this concept with the light cigarettes back in the day, which turned out to be a big lie, since they are just as harmful as the regular ones.

Makes sense, I believe my addiction isn't with the chemicals and how my body craves them but from the ritual of getting away from people and seeing the smoke come out of my mouth, i don't really enjoy the feeling of the smoke in my lungs
Good point 10072 - the habit and rituals around smoking make it just as hard to quit as the nicotine. How do you feel about quitting right now? How motivated are you?

I'm actually really motivated to smoke, i can feel myself running out of breath during work and during my workouts but stressful situations seem to keep bringing back to square one, like today with work being slow and getting spoken to by my boss about a mistake i made
So stress is a big trigger for you 10072. Are these the only situations when you crave a smoke?
No i like smoking when i drink and usually around my friends when we smoke pot, it helps keep the anxiety away and keep my mind at ease

thanks for sharing 10072. These are situations that trigger smoking for many people. We will talk more about ways to handle these in the weeks to come. How confident are you that you can quit smoking and have you already thought about setting a quit day? It's ok if you haven't, I am just curious.

I had a quit day a long time ago and almost every week after but i keep pushing myself into smoking, i'd like to set one for the end of this month after the bad weather, valentines day, and once i have more work experience and have a lesser chance of messing up during work to keep my attitud
Up
Sounds like a plan 10072! With your permission I will keep asking about your quit day in the next weeks to come. How confident are you that you can quit successfully?
I'm actually not that confident about it, i almost dont feel like quiting, as of now, but when i begin my crossfit I'm sure my attitude will change
That's ok 10072 - we are here to work with you to improve this confidence. Your training will help you become more confident. What else would make you more confident?
Sorry I've got to run. See you next week!

data.message: Hi everyone - I am getting ready to start with session 1. Feel free to stop by!

Hi everyone, I've just finished session 1. All the content is on the wall of this event - check it out and maybe you are interested in joining me for the next session next week. See you tomorrow for the "The Doctor Is In" Q&A session. Bye.

That’s all for today’s session!Use the TSP group through your quit date!Also, start discussing your stop smoking goals with the people you listed in Section 2 of your quit plan, and keep your Smoking, Mood, and Activities log updated!Have a great week!
I want to show you something we call the “Daily Tracking of Smoking, Mood, and Activities” log.
You can use it to better understand your smoking by tracking your pleasant activities, mood, and cigs smoked each day.

You should keep it in a place where you can see it every day and notice pleasant activities, mood (faces) and cigs.So, where is the best place for you?... An image on your phone? A photo on FB? Printing it and putting in on your fridge or bathroom mirror??

The goal is to notice patterns in your pleasant activities, mood, and cigs, so it's important to track them often.As you are thinking about quitting, you want to increase your pleasant activities – this will help you with your mood and with quitting cigarettes.
I'm going to put it on my door
Try it for today as an example…Looking at the Mood log above, what are your stats for today? (You can use an emoticon for the mood if you want)

Now, I want you to take another quick survey, this time about your reasons for quitting:https://ucsf.co1.qualtrics.com/SE/?SID=SV_bHfZzczARW9HBOJWhen you’re done, tell me which categories you scored a 9 or higher.
data.name: Do You Want to Change Your Smoking Habits?
data.caption: ucsf.co1.qualtrics.com
data.description: Survey Software, Enterprise Survey software for enterprise feedback management and CRM solutions. Enables high-quality data collection, panel management and results analysis. Perfect for market research or CRM solution (Customer Relationship Management) integration. Free trial and consultation.

data.message: I scored a 12 in health and 11 in the rest.

Ok wow - plenty of reasons for you then. A high score on Health suggests that the hazards of smoking may be enough to make you want to quit now. A high score on Example suggests you want to set a good example for others. A high score in Esthetics suggests you recognize and are disturbed by some of the unpleasant aspects of smoking. A high score in Mastery suggests you are bothered by the fact that you cannot control your desire to smoke.
Does this fit with why you want to quit?
Are you still with me 10093?
Yeah. I'm sick of always stinking and being short on breath and wasting money. And I want to set a good example for my daughter
Those are great reasons! Remind yourself of those going forward.
I apologize I had to run to the.store
No worries - I have posted the rest of the content of todays session. Check out the mood log - maybe that is something you find useful and have a look at the 5 steps!
5. BE PREPARED FOR RELAPSE OR DIFFICULT SITUATIONS:- Avoid alcohol- Be careful around other smokers- Improve your mood in ways other than smoking- Eat a healthy diet and stay active
Which of these will be most helpful to you?

4. GET MEDICATION AND USE IT CORRECTLY:Talk with your health care provider about which medication will work best for you:- Medication: bupropion, varenicline (prescription).- Nicotine Replacement: gum & patch (over-the-counter), inhaler & nasal spray (prescription)
Are there one of these that you think would be helpful for you?

3. LEARN NEW SKILLS AND BEHAVIORS.- When you first try to quit, change your routine.- Reduce stress.- Distract yourself from urges to smoke.- Plan something enjoyable to do every day.- Drink a lot of water and other fluids.
Which of these will be most helpful to you?
2. GET SUPPORT AND ENCOURAGEMENT:- Tell your family, friends and coworkers you are quitting.- Talk to your doctor or other health care provider.- Get group, individual, or telephone counseling.
Who can support you with quitting smoking?

Try this SHORT survey about why you smoke (Don’t worry it’s easy)STOP when you get your score. https://ucsf.co1.qualtrics.com/SE/?SID=SV_73dz87ACkEB28vPWhich categories did you score 11 or higher? If you didn’t score 11 or higher in any of them, which were your 2 highest scores?
data.name: Why Do You Smoke?
data.caption: ucsf.co1.qualtrics.com
data.description: Survey Software, Enterprise Survey software for enterprise feedback management and CRM solutions. Enables high-quality data collection, panel management and results analysis. Perfect for market research or CRM solution (Customer Relationship Management) integration. Free trial and consultation.

data.message: 11 for pleasurable relaxation and 13 for "crutch"

A high score in Stimulation suggests that you are a smoker who is stimulated by the cigarette — you feel that it helps wake you, organize your thoughts, and keep you going.A high score in Handling suggests that you feel satisfied by handling cigarettes.A high score in Pleasure Relaxation suggests that using cigarettes makes you feel good.A high score in Crutch: Tension Reduction suggests you use cigarettes as a crutch in moments of stress or discomfort.A high score in Craving: Psychological Addiction suggests you are psychologically addicted to cigarettes. Quitting smoking is difficult for the person who is psychologically addicted.A high score in Habit suggests that you no longer getting much satisfaction from cigarettes.
Does that fit with why you think you smoke?
Yes. I mostly just smoke when I'm relaxed or stressed oddly haha
Ok, good to know. It is really useful to know your reasons for smoking, so you can be aware of your triggers or high risk situations. Remind yourself of those reasons going forward.
First I'm interested to find out a little about your smoking habits: How much are you smoking right now? Like how many cigs per day? How many days a week?
About half a pack every day
Alright, and what are your current goals for quitting?
I'd like to quit permanently. I don't want to waste money to kill myself anymore
Ok that's great to hear - I think these sessions can really provide you with some extra skills and motivation!
Cool thank you.
Hi guys, this is Dr. Johannes Thrul from TSP. Are you ready to get started with your first session?
Attending these will really increase your chances of quitting tobacco (if you desire to do so) – so let’s get started!

That's all for this session!! I am proud of you! Between now and next session please continue to work on your risk situations, use your alternatives to cope with stress and look to your fiancé and family for support!
Hopefully by next session ill be down to no cigarettes. Thank.you for everything.
Sure you are welcome! See you next week and keep up the great work!
It’s important to remind yourself and others for why you’re quitting. In our last few minutes how about you share your most important reason for quitting?
I have a little girl on the way that I need to be healthy and set a good example for, also I need to spend the money for cigarettes on diapers and such.
Congratulations! A baby is a very powerful reason to quit. Keep reminding yourself why you want to quit.

We have already talked about your risk situations (stress) and how you plan to counter them, so I am not going into any more details here. However, I encourage you to refer to a table that I call “After Your Last Cigarette.” It explains what to expect after having your last cig—from 20 mins after to 5 yrs after! Here’s what it looks like:
I recommend taping it to your fridge/mirror, and posting it on your FB page telling everyone where you are on the table based on how long you’ve quit.
Any initial thoughts about this?
I definitely need to print a few of these out and put it on my door in my fridge and keep one with me.
Yes - they can be a great motivator!
You can also just save the pic on your phone so you always have it available to motivate you.
Have you experienced any withdrawal symptoms yet as you reduced your smoking?
If you haven’t already, try these strategies if you notice any withdrawal symptoms.
What do you think would work well for you?
Irritability definitely. I cope with it well I think though. I have trouble sleeping anyway usually
Great, I am glad to hear that you are coping well. Feel free to try any of the suggestions from the pic above that you think may work for you.
So last time… I suggested that you tell your supporters (family, friends) that you wanted to quit. How did that go?
My fiance is super excited. She hates cigarettes more than anything. My parents, especially my dad, are super supportive. And anyone else I've told thinks it's awesome that I'm trying.g to.quit
Good job - it sounds like you have a great support system in place!
How do you feel about your quitting now? Would you say you’re still committed to stay smoke free?
Definitely. I'm absolutely determined to quit
I love hearing that!
Let’s review the Mood Log.Remember this?
What are your stats for today? (Mood, pleasant activities, number of cigs smoked)
I'm in a great mood today. I've gotten a lot done, just came back from a wonderful dinner and I've only had a.couple cigs!
Did you notice any patterns between the # of pleasant activities, mood, and # of cigarettes smoked since our last session?
Well yeah obviously the more pleasant things I do the happier I am and the less time I have to smoke
sorry - I meant to say: That's understandable. What triggers led you to smoke this week? What was going on?
Well honestly I've kind of been.stressing over finances and getting my own place. Among other things.
Yeah that does sound stressful - but yeah you managed to reduce your number of cigs quite dramatically and you even didn't smoke at all on one day - that's pretty impressive!
Smoking has definitely lost its appeal for me. I smoke and walk up a flight of stairs and can't breathe.
I understand that does not sound very pleasant. Keep reminding yourself of your reasons to quit moving forward!

Let’s go back to the quit plan developed in the first session and see what worked and what didn’t. We talked about difficult situations and how to deal with them. Do you remember what you said in this section of the TSP quit plan?
I've been trying to avoid stressful situations whether by cleaning up or just playing on my phone
That's great - I think you should just keep doing that and over time you will get better at dealing with stressful situations and not smoke :)
Welcome to our 2nd session!To start off…what is your smoking status (how much you smoke)? What is your quit date (if you have one)?
I'm actively trying to quit now. I've smoked only a couple of cigarettes in the past couple of days.
Wow great job! Have you decided to set a quit date yet?
Also, how are you holding up with reducing the cigarettes you smoke? Is it hard? Is it easy? What strategy are you using?
Are you still there 10093?
I'd like to not have any cigs Saturday. Maybe only a.couple Friday. I've been doing good cutting backI had four yesterday and two so far today. And that's down from a half a pack
Good job!
